   "topic": "Malignant spinal cord compression — dexamethasone FIRST, then MRI whole spine, then definitive Rx",
   "subarea": "Oncological emergencies",
   "trap": "Sequence and dose are the gotcha. Give DEXAMETHASONE immediately on clinical suspicion — do NOT wait for the MRI. Standard Australian practice: dexamethasone 16 mg/day (commonly 8 mg IV/PO BD, or a one-off 16 mg loading dose then 16 mg daily) with PPI cover and BSL monitoring. (High-dose 96 mg/day was studied in TROG SuperDEX but is NOT routine — extra toxicity, no clear benefit.) Imaging = MRI of the WHOLE spine (not just the symptomatic level) within 24 h, because ~1/3 have multiple levels. Definitive treatment = radiotherapy OR surgical decompression — surgery (Patchell) is preferred if good performance status, single level, spinal instability, unknown histology needing tissue, or radioresistant tumour.",
   "whatFirst": "Steroids first (within minutes of suspicion), MRI whole spine within 24 h second, neurosurgery/radiation oncology referral third. Pre-treatment ambulatory status is the strongest predictor of post-treatment walking — so time-to-treatment is everything.",
   "discriminator": "Discriminate cord compression (UMN: hyperreflexia, up-going plantars, sensory level, a level on the trunk) from cauda equina (LMN: areflexia, saddle anaesthesia, early bladder/bowel — below L1/L2). Both are emergencies; both get steroids + urgent MRI. Distinguish new back pain in a cancer patient (red flag) from mechanical back pain — nocturnal/recumbent worsening and thoracic pain point to metastatic cord compression.",
   "redFlags": "New/worsening back pain in any cancer patient, radicular pain, leg weakness, sensory level, urinary retention/incontinence, saddle anaesthesia -> treat as MSCC, give steroids, urgent MRI. Established paraplegia >24-48 h has poor recovery prognosis — but still image and treat for pain/stability.",
