   "topic": "Raised intracranial pressure from brain metastases — dexamethasone + the seizure-prophylaxis trap",
   "subarea": "Oncological emergencies",
   "trap": "An often-missed oncological emergency. Symptomatic vasogenic oedema around brain mets -> DEXAMETHASONE (commonly 8-16 mg/day, e.g. 4 mg q6h; loading 8-10 mg) with PPI cover — steroids treat the oedema, not the tumour. The gotcha: do NOT give prophylactic anticonvulsants to brain-met patients who have NOT had a seizure (no proven benefit, drug interactions, toxicity) — only treat those who HAVE seized. Definitive options = whole-brain RT, stereotactic radiosurgery (limited number of mets), or surgery (single accessible met / mass effect / unknown primary). Avoid over-aggressive lowering of BP. For impending herniation, add measures to lower ICP (head up, consider mannitol/hypertonic saline) and urgent neurosurgical referral.",
