   "topic": "Cancer referral RED FLAGS - the symptoms that mandate urgent work-up regardless of a normal screen",
   "subarea": "Cancer principles & screening",
   "trap": "The single biggest exam trap is using a SCREENING test (or a recent normal screen) for a SYMPTOMATIC patient. Screening is for the asymptomatic - any red-flag symptom needs a DIAGNOSTIC pathway. Key Australian red flags by site: unexplained weight loss / night sweats / new lump; iron-deficiency anaemia (esp. men/postmenopausal women) -> GI work-up; rectal bleeding or change in bowel habit; postmenopausal, postcoital or intermenstrual bleeding; haematuria (visible, painless) -> urology; persistent cough/haemoptysis in a smoker; dysphagia; jaundice; new bone pain; breast lump/nipple change/skin tethering; unexplained lymphadenopathy.",
   "whatFirst": "Red-flag symptom -> diagnostic referral/imaging now; do NOT reassure on the basis of a normal screening test. Painless visible haematuria, dysphagia, and a breast lump are 'refer regardless' flags.",
   "discriminator": "Screening (asymptomatic, programmatic) vs diagnostic assessment (symptomatic). A normal screening mammogram/iFOBT/HPV does NOT exclude cancer in a person with symptoms - the false-negative rate is real and the lesion may be interval/new.",
   "redFlags": "Visible painless haematuria, dysphagia, haemoptysis, postmenopausal bleeding, iron-deficiency anaemia, unexplained weight loss, a hard fixed lymph node, or a breast lump = urgent referral.",
