   "subarea": "Cancer principles & screening",
   "trap": "Numbers examiners love: oral-to-subcut MORPHINE is roughly 2:1 (oral dose / 2 = subcut/24h via syringe driver); oral MORPHINE to oral OXYCODONE is roughly 1.5:1; the BREAKTHROUGH (PRN) dose = 1/10 to 1/6 of the total 24-hour oral opioid dose (1/6 is the classic teaching figure; some Australian charts use 1/10-1/12), given ~hourly-to-4-hourly PRN. When ROTATING opioids for toxicity, reduce the calculated equivalent dose by ~25-50% for incomplete cross-tolerance. In renal impairment AVOID morphine (active metabolite M6G accumulates -> neurotoxicity) - use HYDROMORPHONE or FENTANYL. Always co-prescribe a regular laxative (opioids cause constipation - no tolerance develops) and an as-needed antiemetic.",
   "whatFirst": "New cancer pain on a stable background opioid -> calculate the 24-hour total, set breakthrough at 1/10-1/6, and titrate. Opioid TOXICITY (drowsiness, myoclonus, pinpoint pupils, confusion, RR depression) -> reduce/rotate opioid, ensure hydration, treat reversible causes; naloxone ONLY if life-threatening respiratory depression (small titrated doses to avoid acute pain/withdrawal).",
   "discriminator": "Opioid toxicity/neurotoxicity (myoclonus, hyperalgesia, delirium - often with renal decline or dehydration) vs disease progression - the former improves with dose reduction/rotation + hydration. Terminal delirium vs reversible delirium (opioids, hypercalcaemia, sepsis, urinary retention) - look for the reversible cause first.",
   "redFlags": "Respiratory rate < 8 with reduced consciousness = significant opioid-induced respiratory depression -> titrated naloxone. Persistent myoclonus/agitation on rising opioid = neurotoxicity, rotate and reduce.",
