   "topic": "PSA testing in Australia - no NHMRC-approved population program, shared decision-making, and the draft 2025 shift",
   "subarea": "Cancer principles & screening",
   "trap": "There is NO NHMRC-approved population PSA screening program (unlike bowel/breast/cervical) because of overdiagnosis/overtreatment - but the GUIDANCE is shifting. The expired 2016 guidelines said: offer PSA only after SHARED DECISION-MAKING; if the man opts in and is average risk, PSA every 2 years from 50-69. The DRAFT 2025 PCFA/Cancer Council guidelines (NHMRC approval pending) go further: a STRONG recommendation for GPs to OFFER 2-yearly PSA to all men aged 50-69, plus a baseline PSA at age 40 to risk-stratify, and PSA from 40 (2-yearly) for higher-risk/Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander men. The draft also drops routine DRE in primary care in favour of mpMRI before biopsy. PSA is NOT cancer-specific - it rises with BPH, prostatitis, UTI, recent ejaculation, DRE and instrumentation.",
   "whatFirst": "Before any PSA in an asymptomatic man: have the benefits/harms conversation (overdiagnosis -> biopsy complications, treatment-related incontinence/erectile dysfunction). A raised PSA -> repeat to confirm + arrange mpMRI before deciding on biopsy (modern pathway), not automatic immediate biopsy.",
   "discriminator": "Screening (asymptomatic, shared decision/offer, opportunistic) vs investigating symptoms (LUTS, bone pain, weight loss -> investigate regardless). Benign PSA rise (BPH/prostatitis/recent ejaculation) vs cancer - avoid testing within ~48 h of ejaculation/DRE/cycling; treat and recheck if infection suspected.",
   "redFlags": "Bone pain, very high PSA, hard craggy nodular prostate on DRE, obstructive renal failure -> urgent urology referral for likely advanced disease.",
   "mcqTrap": "Tempting wrong answer: 'a normal PSA excludes prostate cancer' (it does not), or treating it as a mandated mailed-out population program like bowel/breast/cervical (it is not - testing is OFFERED/opt-in after discussion). Also 'do a DRE first to decide on PSA' - draft 2025 guidance no longer recommends routine primary-care DRE, favouring mpMRI before biopsy.",
   "mnemonic": "No mailed program - it's OFFERED; 50-69 every 2 yr; 2025 draft adds baseline PSA at 40; PSA isn't cancer-specific.",
   "viva": "Out loud: 'Australia has no NHMRC-approved population PSA program because of overdiagnosis, so I'd have a shared-decision conversation about benefits and harms; for an average-risk man who opts in, PSA every 2 years from 50 to 69 - and the draft 2025 guidelines now also support offering a baseline PSA at 40. A raised PSA I'd confirm on repeat and arrange MRI before any biopsy.'",
