   "topic": "Tumour lysis syndrome - the metabolic quartet, the urate-lowering choice, and what NOT to give",
   "subarea": "Cancer principles & screening",
   "trap": "TLS is most common in BULKY, rapidly-proliferating, chemo-SENSITIVE cancers (high-grade lymphoma - Burkitt, ALL/AML) shortly after starting treatment. The diagnostic quartet: HYPERkalaemia, HYPERphosphataemia, HYPERuricaemia, and HYPOcalcaemia (calcium falls as phosphate rises) -> risk of AKI and fatal arrhythmia. Prevention/treatment: aggressive IV HYDRATION + urate-lowering: ALLOPURINOL for prophylaxis (low-moderate risk), but RASBURICASE for high-risk/established TLS (it enzymatically degrades EXISTING urate; allopurinol does not). Do NOT give calcium for asymptomatic hypocalcaemia (calcium-phosphate precipitation -> worsens AKI); only treat symptomatic hypocalcaemia/arrhythmia. Do NOT co-administer allopurinol with rasburicase (reduces rasburicase effectiveness).",
   "whatFirst": "High-risk patient starting chemo -> IV fluids + allopurinol (or rasburicase if high risk) BEFORE/with first cycle, plus close electrolyte monitoring. Established TLS -> hydrate, rasburicase, manage hyperkalaemia, dialysis if refractory AKI/K+.",
   "discriminator": "Rasburicase vs allopurinol: allopurinol PREVENTS new urate formation (xanthine oxidase inhibitor) but doesn't clear existing urate; rasburicase ENZYMATICALLY degrades existing uric acid - use it when urate is already high or risk is high. Rasburicase is CONTRAINDICATED in G6PD deficiency (haemolysis/methaemoglobinaemia) - test G6PD in at-risk patients first.",
   "redFlags": "Rising K+, falling urine output/rising creatinine, ECG changes (peaked T waves) in a patient just started on chemo for a bulky haematological malignancy = TLS - emergency.",
   "mcqTrap": "Tempting wrong answer: 'give IV calcium to correct the hypocalcaemia' (don't, unless symptomatic - precipitates with phosphate and worsens renal injury), or 'allopurinol' when the urate is already very high/high-risk (rasburicase is the better answer there), or adding allopurinol on top of rasburicase.",
   "mnemonic": "High K, high PO4, high urate, LOW Ca; Allopurinol prevents, Rasburicase rescues (not in G6PD); don't chase the calcium.",
   "viva": "Out loud: 'In a patient with bulky high-grade lymphoma starting chemo I'd anticipate tumour lysis - I'd hydrate aggressively, give a urate-lowering agent (allopurinol prophylactically, or rasburicase if high-risk), monitor electrolytes closely, and I would NOT replace asymptomatic hypocalcaemia because of the risk of calcium-phosphate precipitation.'",
