   "topic": "BREAKTHROUGH dose = 1/6 (range 1/12–1/6) of the total 24-hour opioid dose",
   "subarea": "Palliative & symptom control",
   "whatFirst": "Calculate the breakthrough (rescue) dose as ~1/6 of the TOTAL 24-hour opioid dose, given as the immediate-release form of the SAME opioid, repeatable ~q1h PRN (oral) / more frequently parenterally. If the patient needs >3-4 breakthrough doses/day consistently, increase the regular (background) dose.",
   "trap": "Forgetting to add the BACKGROUND plus all BREAKTHROUGH doses when totalling the 24h requirement before recalculating. Also: giving the breakthrough as a long-acting/MR form (wrong — breakthrough must be immediate-release). And calculating breakthrough off the single MR tablet strength rather than the 24h total.",
   "discriminator": "Breakthrough/incident pain (transient, often movement-related) → IR rescue dose 1/6 of 24h dose. Persistent background pain → adjust the regular MR dose. End-of-dose failure (pain returning before next MR dose) → increase MR dose or shorten interval, not just more breakthrough.",
   "redFlags": "Escalating breakthrough requirement (rapidly rising doses, poor response) → reassess for opioid-poorly-responsive pain (neuropathic, bone, incident), consider adjuvant/specialist palliative referral, screen for opioid neurotoxicity (myoclonus, delirium, hyperalgesia).",
