   "whatFirst": "Opioid-naive + uncontrolled cancer pain: start IMMEDIATE-RELEASE oral morphine 2.5-5 mg every 4 hours (regularly q4h if continuous pain) + same dose PRN for breakthrough. Titrate over 2-3 days (increase in ~30-50% increments), then convert the stable 24h requirement to a modified-release (MR/SR) preparation BD. Co-prescribe a regular stimulant laxative from day 1 and a PRN antiemetic.",
   "trap": "The classic MCQ trap is starting a NAIVE patient on modified-release morphine (e.g. MS Contin 10 mg BD) or a fentanyl patch up front. Wrong: you cannot titrate a slow-release drug quickly, and a patch has a ~12-24h onset and long offset — dangerous if you over/under-shoot. IR first, then convert. Fentanyl patches are NEVER for opioid-naive patients or acute/unstable pain.",
   "discriminator": "IR vs MR: IR (morphine elixir/Sevredol) onset ~20-30 min, lasts ~4h — used to FIND the dose and for breakthrough. MR (MS Contin/Kapanol) lasts 12-24h — used only once the requirement is STABLE. Patch (fentanyl/buprenorphine) = stable chronic pain, opioid-tolerant, often when oral route lost — not for titration.",
