   "topic": "OPIOID NEUROTOXICITY (OIN) — myoclonus + delirium + hyperalgesia → ROTATE & hydrate, don't just keep escalating",
   "subarea": "Palliative & symptom control",
   "whatFirst": "Recognise the cluster: MYOCLONUS (jerks), DELIRIUM/agitation, HYPERALGESIA + allodynia (pain worsens/spreads despite more opioid), vivid dreams/hallucinations, sometimes seizures. Management: reduce the opioid dose if pain allows, HYDRATE (helps clear metabolites), treat reversibles (renal function, dehydration, sepsis), and ROTATE to a structurally different opioid at a REDUCED dose; consider adjuvants. Often improves within ~24h.",
   "trap": "Interpreting worsening pain (actually hyperalgesia) as UNDER-treatment and giving MORE opioid → vicious cycle. The exam wants you to recognise that escalating the same opioid makes it worse; the answer is rotate + reduce + hydrate.",
   "discriminator": "OIN vs disease progression: in OIN, more opioid worsens pain (hyperalgesia) and there's myoclonus/delirium; metabolites (M3G) and renal impairment are key drivers. OIN myoclonus vs terminal restlessness vs seizure: OIN myoclonus is multifocal jerking with the other features and a clear opioid/renal context.",
   "redFlags": "Renal impairment / dehydration / high parenteral morphine doses = high risk (esp. morphine via M3G/M6G accumulation) → in renal failure prefer fentanyl (or cautious hydromorphone). Seizures, severe delirium → urgent review, benzodiazepine for myoclonus (e.g. clonazepam/midazolam), specialist palliative input.",
   "mcqTrap": "'Increase the morphine dose' for a patient whose pain is worsening AND who is jerking/confused on high-dose morphine with renal impairment — the tempting 'treat the pain' answer, but it is OIN: correct = rotate to a different opioid at reduced dose + hydrate (e.g. switch morphine→fentanyl/hydromorphone in renal failure).",
