   "topic": "SYRINGE DRIVER (CSCI) — when oral route is lost; what NOT to mix and how to convert",
   "subarea": "Palliative & symptom control",
   "whatFirst": "Use a continuous SC infusion (syringe driver, e.g. Niki T34/CADD) when the ORAL route fails (unable to swallow, vomiting, reduced consciousness, malabsorption, last days of life). Convert the 24h oral opioid to the SC equivalent (oral morphine→SC morphine ÷ ~2-3), set the breakthrough as 1/6 of the SC 24h dose given as SC PRN, and combine compatible drugs (opioid + antiemetic ± antisecretory ± sedative) in one driver. Continue regular PRN charting alongside.",
   "trap": "Assuming a syringe driver is only for 'the actively dying' / that starting one means imminent death — it is simply a delivery route for any patient who can't take oral meds. Another trap: putting INCOMPATIBLE drugs together (notably cyclizine + hyoscine butylbromide, or cyclizine at high concentration → crystallisation/precipitation) or mixing dexamethasone with most other drugs (precipitation) — dexamethasone usually given separately.",
   "discriminator": "Syringe driver (continuous SC) vs PRN SC bolus vs transdermal patch: driver gives steady levels and flexible titration of multiple symptoms; patch suits STABLE pain with intact requirements but is slow to adjust. If already on a fentanyl patch and now dying, LEAVE the patch on and add a driver for additional/other symptoms.",
   "redFlags": "Site reaction (erythema, swelling, leakage) → resite. Check for precipitation/cloudiness in the syringe (incompatibility) → review combination. Breakthrough still required → ensure PRN doses charted (1/6 of 24h SC dose). Sudden uncontrolled symptoms → ISBAR to palliative care/after-hours.",
   "mcqTrap": "'A syringe driver is indicated because the patient is dying' — partially true but the EXAM point is the indication is LOSS OF THE ORAL ROUTE, not prognosis. Also trap: 'give the same mg of morphine SC as they took orally' (ignores the oral→SC ratio → overdose).",
   "source": "eTG Palliative (current); CareSearch/PalliAGED CSCI guidance; NSW CEC Last Days of Life resources.",
   "viva": "Examiner: 'Patient can't swallow their morphine and metoclopramide — what now?' Answer: convert to SC syringe driver (apply oral→SC ratio), combine compatible drugs, set SC breakthrough at 1/6, chart PRNs. Discriminator: incompatible mixes; patch + driver coexistence.",
   "mnemonic": "DRIVER = Delivery route when oral lost; Recalc oral→SC (halve morphine); Incompatibles out (watch cyclizine, dexamethasone); Verify breakthrough 1/6; Evaluate site; Reassure (not a death sentence).",
